'''Relative apparent synapomorphy analysis''', or '''RASA''', is a method that aims to determine whether a given character is shared between [[Taxon|taxa]] due to [[shared ancestry]] or due to [[Convergence (biology)|convergence]]. A [[synapomorphy]] is a shared trait found among two or more taxa and their most recent common ancestor, whose ancestor in turn does not possess the trait. RASA assigns a score to the character based on its potential to be informative.<ref>{{cite journal | url = http://mbe.oxfordjournals.org/content/13/6/749.short | pmid = 8754211 | year = 1996 | last1 = Lyons-Weiler | first1 = J | last2 = Hoelzer | first2 = GA | last3 = Tausch | first3 = RJ | title = Relative apparent synapomorphy analysis (RASA). I: The statistical measurement of phylogenetic signal | volume = 13 | issue = 6 | pages = 749–57 | journal = Molecular Biology and Evolution | doi=10.1093/oxfordjournals.molbev.a025635}}</ref>
==Limitations== The method performs poorly when used to select an outgroup taxon, to quantify the amount of [[Phylogenetics|phylogenetic signal]] present, or to identify taxa that may be prone to [[long branch attraction]].<ref>{{Cite journal | url = http://mbe.oxfordjournals.org/content/19/1/14.abstract | pmid = 11752186 | year = 2002 | last1 = Simmons | first1 = MP | last2 = Randle | first2 = CP | last3 = Freudenstein | first3 = JV | last4 = Wenzel | first4 = JW | title = Limitations of relative apparent synapomorphy analysis (RASA) for measuring phylogenetic signal | volume = 19 | issue = 1 | pages = 14–23 | journal = Molecular Biology and Evolution | doi=10.1093/oxfordjournals.molbev.a003978 }}</ref>
